---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import AdUnit from '../../components/AdUnit.astro';
import { getWorksheetBySlug } from '../../data/worksheets';
import '../../styles/worksheet.css';

const ws = getWorksheetBySlug('triangle-worksheets')!;

const structuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://toolcalcs.com/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Worksheets", "item": "https://toolcalcs.com/worksheets/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Triangle Worksheets" }
  ]
};
---

<BaseLayout title="Free Triangle Worksheets - Printable Math Practice | ToolCalcs" description={ws.description} type="article" structuredData={structuredData}>
  <nav class="breadcrumb">
    <a href="/">Home</a> &rsaquo;
    <a href="/worksheets/">Worksheets</a> &rsaquo;
    <span>Triangle Worksheets</span>
  </nav>

  <h1>{ws.title}</h1>
  <p class="page-desc">{ws.description}</p>

  <div class="worksheet-box">
    <div class="config-panel">
      <h3>Settings</h3>
      <div class="config-inputs">
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgProblems">Number of Problems</label>
          <input type="number" id="cfgProblems" value="12" min="8" max="20" />
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgType">Problem Type</label>
          <select id="cfgType">
            <option value="area">Find Area</option>
            <option value="perimeter">Find Perimeter</option>
            <option value="missingAngle">Find Missing Angle</option>
            <option value="mixed" selected>Mixed</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="config-group">
          <label for="cfgDifficulty">Difficulty</label>
          <select id="cfgDifficulty">
            <option value="easy" selected>Easy</option>
            <option value="medium">Medium</option>
            <option value="hard">Hard</option>
          </select>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-actions">
      <button class="ws-btn primary" id="btnGenerate">Generate New</button>
      <button class="ws-btn print" id="btnPrint">Print</button>
      <label class="toggle-label">
        <input type="checkbox" id="toggleAnswers" />
        Show Answers
      </label>
    </div>

    <div class="worksheet-content" id="worksheetContent">
      <div class="worksheet-header-print">
        <h2>Triangle Practice</h2>
        <div class="name-date">
          <span>Name: ___________________</span>
          <span>Date: ___________________</span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-grid" id="problemGrid"></div>
      <div class="answer-key hidden" id="answerKey">
        <h3>Answer Key</h3>
        <div class="answer-grid" id="answerGrid"></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-mid" format="rectangle" />

  <article class="content-section">
    <h2>Understanding Triangles</h2>
    <p>A triangle is a polygon with three sides, three vertices, and three interior angles. It is one of the most fundamental shapes in geometry and appears everywhere in the real world, from the structural trusses of bridges to the slices of pizza on your plate. Every triangle, regardless of its shape or size, shares one critical property: the sum of its three interior angles is always exactly 180 degrees. This angle sum property is the foundation for many triangle calculations and proofs.</p>
    <p>These free printable triangle worksheets help students practice three essential triangle skills: calculating the area using the base-height formula, finding the perimeter by summing all three sides, and determining a missing angle using the 180-degree rule. Each worksheet generates fresh random problems for unlimited practice at adjustable difficulty levels.</p>

    <h2>Triangle Area Formula</h2>
    <p>The area of a triangle measures the amount of flat surface enclosed by its three sides. The formula is:</p>
    <p><strong>A = &frac12; &times; base &times; height</strong></p>
    <p>The base can be any one of the triangle's three sides. The height (also called the altitude) is the perpendicular distance from the chosen base to the opposite vertex. It is critical that the height forms a right angle with the base; if you measure along a slanted side instead, the result will be incorrect.</p>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Find the area of a triangle with base 10 cm and height 6 cm.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>A = &frac12; &times; 10 &times; 6 = &frac12; &times; 60 = 30 cm&sup2;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>The formula works because a triangle is exactly half of a parallelogram with the same base and height. This connection helps students understand why we multiply by one half.</p>

    <h2>Triangle Perimeter Formula</h2>
    <p>The perimeter of a triangle is the total distance around it, found by adding all three side lengths:</p>
    <p><strong>P = a + b + c</strong></p>
    <p>where a, b, and c are the lengths of the three sides. Perimeter is one of the simplest geometry calculations, but it requires students to identify all three side lengths correctly and add them without error.</p>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> Find the perimeter of a triangle with sides 7 cm, 9 cm, and 12 cm.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>P = 7 + 9 + 12 = 28 cm</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Unlike area (which is measured in square units), perimeter is measured in the same linear units as the sides. If the sides are in centimeters, the perimeter is in centimeters.</p>

    <h2>The Angle Sum Property</h2>
    <p>The single most important fact about triangles is that the three interior angles always add up to 180&deg;. This means that if you know two of the three angles, you can always find the third by subtracting the known angles from 180&deg;.</p>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> A triangle has angles of 55&deg; and 80&deg;. Find the third angle.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Third angle = 180&deg; - 55&deg; - 80&deg; = 45&deg;</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Another example:</strong> A right triangle has one angle of 90&deg; and another of 35&deg;. Find the third angle.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Third angle = 180&deg; - 90&deg; - 35&deg; = 55&deg;</li>
    </ul>
    <p>This property has been proven in many ways throughout mathematical history and is one of the first formal geometric principles that students encounter.</p>

    <h2>Types of Triangles</h2>
    <h3>By Sides</h3>
    <p>An <strong>equilateral triangle</strong> has all three sides equal in length and all three angles equal to 60&deg;. An <strong>isosceles triangle</strong> has exactly two sides of equal length, with the angles opposite those sides also equal. A <strong>scalene triangle</strong> has all three sides of different lengths and all three angles different.</p>

    <h3>By Angles</h3>
    <p>An <strong>acute triangle</strong> has all three angles less than 90&deg;. A <strong>right triangle</strong> has exactly one 90&deg; angle. An <strong>obtuse triangle</strong> has one angle greater than 90&deg;. Understanding these classifications helps students predict what types of answers to expect. For instance, a right triangle always has a 90&deg; angle, so the other two must sum to exactly 90&deg;.</p>

    <h2>Grade-Level Guide for Triangle Worksheets</h2>
    <h3>Fifth Grade (Ages 10-11)</h3>
    <p>Fifth graders learn the basics of triangle geometry. They calculate area using the base-height formula with whole numbers, find perimeters by adding three given sides, and use the angle sum property to find a missing angle when the other two are given. Start with "Easy" difficulty, which uses small whole numbers and straightforward problems. Use a single problem type at first (such as "Find Area" only) before switching to "Mixed" once students are comfortable with each type individually.</p>

    <h3>Sixth Grade (Ages 11-12)</h3>
    <p>Sixth graders apply triangle skills more independently. They handle larger numbers, recognize when to use area versus perimeter, and work with the angle sum property in a variety of contexts. Use "Medium" difficulty with the "Mixed" type for a balanced challenge. Students should be able to identify which formula to use based on what the problem asks and explain their reasoning step by step.</p>

    <h3>Seventh Grade (Ages 12-13)</h3>
    <p>Seventh graders encounter triangles with decimal measurements, more complex angle relationships, and multi-step problems. They may also be introduced to the Pythagorean theorem for right triangles. Use "Hard" difficulty with "Mixed" type to prepare for pre-algebra geometry. At this level, students should be precise with decimal arithmetic and comfortable verifying their answers.</p>

    <h2>The Pythagorean Theorem (Introduction)</h2>
    <p>While a full treatment of the Pythagorean theorem is beyond the scope of these worksheets, it is worth introducing. For any right triangle with legs <em>a</em> and <em>b</em> and hypotenuse <em>c</em>:</p>
    <p><strong>a&sup2; + b&sup2; = c&sup2;</strong></p>
    <p>For example, the famous 3-4-5 right triangle: 3&sup2; + 4&sup2; = 9 + 16 = 25 = 5&sup2;. Other common Pythagorean triples include 5-12-13, 8-15-17, and 7-24-25. Knowing these triples helps students quickly identify right triangles and verify side lengths.</p>

    <h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Using the wrong height for area.</strong> The height must be perpendicular to the base. Students sometimes use a slanted side instead of the true altitude, leading to incorrect areas. Always look for the right-angle marker.</li>
      <li><strong>Forgetting to divide by 2 in the area formula.</strong> The area of a triangle is half the product of base and height. Leaving out the division by 2 gives the area of a parallelogram, not a triangle.</li>
      <li><strong>Angle sum errors.</strong> When finding the missing angle, students sometimes subtract from 360&deg; (the sum for quadrilaterals) instead of 180&deg;. Remind them that triangles have three angles summing to 180&deg;.</li>
      <li><strong>Mixing up area and perimeter.</strong> Area measures the surface inside the triangle (in square units), while perimeter measures the distance around it (in linear units). Students should read the question carefully to determine which is being asked.</li>
      <li><strong>Adding only two sides for perimeter.</strong> A triangle has three sides. Students occasionally forget to include all three when calculating the perimeter.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Tips for Parents and Teachers</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Use physical models.</strong> Have students build triangles with straws or craft sticks. Measuring the sides and angles of physical models makes area and perimeter tangible.</li>
      <li><strong>Tear-off proof for angles.</strong> Have students draw a triangle, label the three angles, tear off the corners, and arrange them along a straight line. This demonstrates that the angles sum to 180&deg; (a straight angle).</li>
      <li><strong>Teach one type at a time.</strong> Start with area, then perimeter, then missing angles. Once each is comfortable, use "Mixed" mode to build flexibility in switching between problem types.</li>
      <li><strong>Connect to real-world triangles.</strong> Find triangles in architecture, road signs, and nature. Estimate their dimensions and calculate area or perimeter for practical practice.</li>
      <li><strong>Encourage showing work.</strong> Writing out each step (formula, substitution, calculation) helps students catch errors and reinforces the process.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>How to Use These Triangle Worksheets</h2>
    <p>Select the number of problems, problem type, and difficulty using the settings above. Click "Generate New" for a fresh worksheet. "Find Area" problems give base and height and ask for the area using A = &frac12; &times; base &times; height. "Find Perimeter" problems give three side lengths and ask for their sum. "Find Missing Angle" problems give two of the three angles and ask for the third using the 180&deg; rule. "Mixed" combines all three types randomly. Use "Print" for a clean page and "Show Answers" to reveal solutions.</p>

    <h2>Related Worksheets</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/area-and-perimeter-worksheets/">Area &amp; Perimeter Worksheets</a> - Calculate area and perimeter for rectangles, squares, and triangles.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/geometry-worksheets/">Geometry Worksheets</a> - Identify shapes, classify angles, and find lines of symmetry.</li>
      <li><a href="/worksheets/volume-worksheets/">Volume Worksheets</a> - Calculate volumes of 3D shapes including prisms and cylinders.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>

  <AdUnit slot="ws-bottom" format="horizontal" />
</BaseLayout>

<script is:inline>
  var problems = [];

  function randInt(min, max) {
    return Math.floor(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min;
  }

  function roundTo1(n) {
    return Math.round(n * 10) / 10;
  }

  function generateAreaProblem(diff) {
    var p = {};
    var base, height;

    if (diff === 'easy') {
      base = randInt(3, 20);
      height = randInt(2, 15);
    } else if (diff === 'medium') {
      base = randInt(5, 30);
      height = randInt(3, 25);
    } else {
      base = roundTo1(randInt(30, 200) / 10);
      height = roundTo1(randInt(20, 150) / 10);
    }

    var area = roundTo1(base * height / 2);

    p.type = 'area';
    p.question = 'Find the area of a triangle.';
    p.details = 'Base = ' + base + ' cm, Height = ' + height + ' cm';
    p.formula = 'A = \u00bd \u00d7 base \u00d7 height';
    p.answer = area + ' cm\u00b2';
    return p;
  }

  function generatePerimeterProblem(diff) {
    var p = {};
    var a, b, c;

    if (diff === 'easy') {
      a = randInt(3, 15);
      b = randInt(3, 15);
      // Ensure valid triangle: c must be less than a + b and greater than |a - b|
      var cMin = Math.abs(a - b) + 1;
      var cMax = a + b - 1;
      if (cMax > 15) cMax = 15;
      if (cMin > cMax) cMin = cMax;
      c = randInt(cMin, cMax);
    } else if (diff === 'medium') {
      a = randInt(5, 25);
      b = randInt(5, 25);
      var cMin = Math.abs(a - b) + 1;
      var cMax = a + b - 1;
      if (cMax > 30) cMax = 30;
      if (cMin > cMax) cMin = cMax;
      c = randInt(cMin, cMax);
    } else {
      a = roundTo1(randInt(30, 200) / 10);
      b = roundTo1(randInt(30, 200) / 10);
      var cMin = Math.abs(a - b) + 0.5;
      var cMax = a + b - 0.5;
      c = roundTo1(randInt(Math.ceil(cMin * 10), Math.floor(cMax * 10)) / 10);
    }

    var perim = roundTo1(a + b + c);

    p.type = 'perimeter';
    p.question = 'Find the perimeter of a triangle.';
    p.details = 'Side a = ' + a + ' cm, Side b = ' + b + ' cm, Side c = ' + c + ' cm';
    p.formula = 'P = a + b + c';
    p.answer = perim + ' cm';
    return p;
  }

  function generateMissingAngleProblem(diff) {
    var p = {};
    var a1, a2, a3;

    if (diff === 'easy') {
      a1 = randInt(25, 80);
      a2 = randInt(25, 140 - a1);
      a3 = 180 - a1 - a2;
    } else if (diff === 'medium') {
      a1 = randInt(15, 100);
      a2 = randInt(10, 160 - a1);
      a3 = 180 - a1 - a2;
    } else {
      a1 = randInt(5, 130);
      a2 = randInt(5, 170 - a1);
      a3 = 180 - a1 - a2;
    }

    // Ensure all angles are positive
    if (a3 < 1) { a1 = 60; a2 = 60; a3 = 60; }

    // Randomly choose which angle to hide
    var hide = randInt(0, 2);
    var angles = [a1, a2, a3];
    var shown = [];
    for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
      if (i !== hide) shown.push(angles[i] + '\u00b0');
      else shown.push('?');
    }

    p.type = 'missingAngle';
    p.question = 'Find the missing angle.';
    p.details = 'Angles: ' + shown.join(', ') + '  (sum = 180\u00b0)';
    p.formula = 'Missing = 180\u00b0 \u2212 known angles';
    p.answer = angles[hide] + '\u00b0';
    return p;
  }

  function generateProblems() {
    var count = parseInt(document.getElementById('cfgProblems').value, 10);
    var type = document.getElementById('cfgType').value;
    var diff = document.getElementById('cfgDifficulty').value;

    if (isNaN(count) || count < 8) count = 8;
    if (count > 20) count = 20;

    problems = [];
    var types = ['area', 'perimeter', 'missingAngle'];

    for (var i = 0; i < count; i++) {
      var problemType = type;
      if (type === 'mixed') {
        problemType = types[Math.floor(Math.random() * types.length)];
      }

      if (problemType === 'area') {
        problems.push(generateAreaProblem(diff));
      } else if (problemType === 'perimeter') {
        problems.push(generatePerimeterProblem(diff));
      } else {
        problems.push(generateMissingAngleProblem(diff));
      }
    }

    renderProblems();
    renderAnswerKey();
    updateAnswerVisibility();
  }

  function renderProblems() {
    var grid = document.getElementById('problemGrid');
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var html = '';

    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      var p = problems[i];
      html += '<div class="problem tri-problem">';
      html += '<div class="problem-number">' + (i + 1) + ')</div>';
      html += '<div class="tri-question">' + p.question + '</div>';
      html += '<div class="tri-formula">' + p.formula + '</div>';
      html += '<div class="tri-details">' + p.details + '</div>';
      html += '<div class="problem-answer' + (showAnswers ? ' revealed' : '') + '">';
      html += showAnswers ? p.answer : '_______________';
      html += '</div>';
      html += '</div>';
    }

    grid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function renderAnswerKey() {
    var answerGrid = document.getElementById('answerGrid');
    var html = '';
    for (var i = 0; i < problems.length; i++) {
      html += '<div class="answer-item">';
      html += '<span class="q">' + (i + 1) + '.</span>';
      html += '<span class="a">' + problems[i].answer + '</span>';
      html += '</div>';
    }
    answerGrid.innerHTML = html;
  }

  function updateAnswerVisibility() {
    var showAnswers = document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').checked;
    var answerKey = document.getElementById('answerKey');
    if (showAnswers) { answerKey.classList.remove('hidden'); }
    else { answerKey.classList.add('hidden'); }
    renderProblems();
  }

  document.getElementById('btnGenerate').addEventListener('click', generateProblems);
  document.getElementById('btnPrint').addEventListener('click', function () { window.print(); });
  document.getElementById('toggleAnswers').addEventListener('change', updateAnswerVisibility);
  generateProblems();
</script>

<style>
  :global(.tri-problem) {
    flex-direction: column !important;
    align-items: flex-start !important;
    gap: 4px;
    min-width: 200px;
  }
  :global(.tri-question) {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-primary);
  }
  :global(.tri-formula) {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  :global(.tri-details) {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }
</style>
